Fingerspelling allows English words to be represented in American Sign Language (ASL) via a series of handshapes, one for every letter of the alphabet. These sequences are produced rapidly and fluidly. It is just one part of ASL, but it is an important part, for several reasons.  As some new words enter ASL via fingerspelling, it is a living laboratory where we can see many of the phonetic processes of the language as a whole. Because the 26 handshape targets are well described, fingerspelling allows us to analyze the factors that influence variation in production&mdash;the signer, as well as the phonetic and phonological context. Because it is a part of ASL where the signed word for each letter of the alphabet consists of handshape and orientation of the hand it is a perfect place to begin sign language recognition in ASL. Handshape/orientation of the hand are the main properties that vary, since typically the location does not change, and except for two letters -J- and -Z-, the movement is a function of the transition between one handshape and the next.  It is an important contact phenomenon between English and ASL, it's possibilties for linking English and ASL vocabulary, it has important implications for signing Deaf children as they are learning to read. It is therefore extremely important in ASL acquisition.
In this dissertation project, KeaneÆs objectives were to:
1) Collect a large corpus of fingerspelled forms, so that his analyses would be based on a large number of data points;
2) Identify factors at work in variation: linguistic context, signer, overall speed, and the proportion of time spent in holding the target handshapes vs. the transitions between them;
3) Provide essential information about fingerspelling to develop an system of automatic recognition of fingerspelled words across signers;
4) Improve techniques for the collection of motion capture data along side regular video data;
5) Develop a semiautomatic method for annotating fingerspelled data;
6) Develop a Hidden Markov Model (HMM) for detecting fingerspelled sequences in the data already collected;
7) Begin to use the analyses of fingerspelled forms produced as stimuli in perception studies; and
8) Disseminate his results.
In his dissertation and subsequent work with colleagues, Keane has accomplished all of these objectives. At the University of Chicago there is the largest set of fingerspelled data of ASL anywhere. KeaneÆs semi-automatic annotation techniques have been developed for and used in his dissertation, and they have also been used in several additional studies. We have now developed a way to align regular video and motion capture data so that they can be analyzed together. The analyses of these data have resulted in 12 publications or conference presentations, which include the use of the production forms as stimuli to be used to understand how fingerspelling is perceived and learned by several groups of ASL learners. Four different open-source software packages were created to help test and represent linguistic theories, process data, and further help researchers doing similar work in the future. Finally, work done on this project is helping current and future projects understand the importance of fingerspelling, and the phonetics and phonology of American Sign Language, broadly speaking.



